                            <div class="flt-text">
                                <div>
                                    <p class="title">
                                        <span>The case for</span>
                                        <span>and against</span>
                                        <span>VLCC orders</span>
                                    </p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <img src="../../../images/1808/column/market_top_visual_m.jpg" class="market_m_bg"/>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <!-- top-visual-area -->
                <div class="con-wrap">
                    <div class="confine-area text_by">
                        <p class="label">
                            Greg Miller, <br>Managing editor of Fairplay by IHS Markit
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="confine-area m_section01">
                        <div class="info_section">
                            <div class="line_design"></div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="txt_wrap">
                            <p class="text">We are now past the half-way point in 2018, and the key issues have come into clearer focus. Here are the top trends and what they could mean to shipping for the remainder of this year:</p>

                            <p class="text tp-2">
                                <span class="outer"><span>Rate disappointment</span></span> <br>
                                Going into this year, sentiment was positive towards container shipping and very positive towards bulkers and product tankers. A half-year on, box shipping is back to losses, dry bulk rates are uninspiring, product-tanker rates are even worse than in 2017, crude-tanker rates are much weaker than predicted, and liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) shipping rates remain well below breakeven. If second-half rates remain depressed for crude, products and LPG tankers, debt restructurings and forced consolidations could ensue.
                            </p>
                            <p class="text tp-2">
                                <span class="outer"><span>Tariffs and trade turmoil</span></span> <br>
                                First came US tariffs on steel and aluminium and counter-tariffs from China, Canada, Mexico, and the European Union. Then came US tariffs specifically targeting China, and Chinese counter-tariffs. The effect on shipping demand in the second half is difficult to predict. Some cargoes will move ahead of tariffs, some will move in spite of them, some will not be shipped at all, and some will reroute. Shipping demand fallout may be less than feared, although car carriers and container ships do appear at risk.
                            </p>
                            <p class="text tp-2">
                                <span class="outer"><span>Bank finance in flux</span></span> <br>
                                Bank-debt capacity continues to contract. Remaining banks are competing to lend to the best borrowers, creating large disparities in loan costs. Meanwhile, debt is covering much less of vessel costs: 40-50% versus 80% previously, so owners need either more equity or higher-cost mezzanine debt. One side effect is that owners are doing sale-and-leaseback deals at an unprecedented pace to fill the gap. Even more sale-and-leasebacks are likely in the second half, and longer term, interest rates paid by even the best-rated shipping borrowers should escalate.
                            </p>
                            <p class="text tp-2">
                                <span class="outer"><span>Wall Street iffy, Oslo open</span></span> <br>
                                Equity and bond offerings continue at a moderate pace in Oslo, but the larger New York market remains problematic. GoodBulk’s failure to complete its US initial public offering and NASDAQ listing is the latest bad omen. Overall, 2018 is shaping up to be one of the worst years ever for common-equity offerings by US-listed companies, which are instead raising cash via sales of preferred shares, convertibles and debt securities. Expect more money-raising by smaller owners in Oslo in the second half, as well as ongoing shakiness on Wall Street.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="wide-back-area">
                        <div class="line_design"></div>
                        <div class="con-outer">
                            <div class="confine">
                                <img src="../../../images/1808/column/market_img1.jpg" class="" alt="" style="width: 100%;">
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="confine-area">
                        <div class="section2">
                            <p class="text">
                                <span class="outer"><span>Surging crude and bunker pricing</span></span> <br>
                                Elevated crude pricing is having two tanker effects: firstly, it is fuelling US crude exports; secondly, it is compelling non-US suppliers to restart some production, which could lead to more second-half flows from the Middle East and Russia. Higher crude pricing is also translating into much higher bunker pricing. The consequences, which should persist through year-end, are lower profit margins for operators of chartered-in tonnage and owners of spot tonnage, and favouritism in charter markets toward fuel-efficient vessels.
                            </p>

                            <p class="text tp-2">
                                <span class="outer"><span>Consolidation continues</span></span> <br>
                                The shipping industry has experienced unprecedented consolidation since 2014. So far this year, Gener8 was sold to Euronav, Star Bulk bought the Augustea Atlantica and Song Bulk fleets, Seaspan acquired Grand China Intermodal, Essberger took over Crystal Nordic, Navios Acquisition is set to merge with Navios Midstream, and BW LPG made a bid – that was spurned – for Dorian LPG. With costs rising, rates limping, and private-equity investors seeking exits, more consolidation should follow.
                            </p>
                            <p class="text tp-2">
                                <span class="outer"><span>LNG outperformance</span></span> <br>
                                Unlike almost all other segments, liquefied natural gas (LNG) shipping is performing extremely well in 2018. Spot rates are hitting annual highs of over USD90,000/day and more vessels are being chartered-in. Newbuilding deliveries pose a risk, but the second half looks rosy for LNG.
                            </p>
                        </div>
